**Kagyu Period (11th-12th Century)**
In the 11th century, Kagyu founder Marpa Lotsawa traveled to India's Nalanda Monastery multiple times to study tantra, bringing back Kalachakra and other tantric texts. The Kagyu school systematically established Kailash as a tantric sacred site. Milarepa's (1052-1135) practice here made Kailash an important Kagyu pilgrimage site.

**Gelug Period (14th Century onward)**
After Tsongkhapa founded the Gelug school, Kailash was incorporated into Gelug sacred geography. During the Fifth Dalai Lama's reign (17th century), the Tibetan government began regulating pilgrimage activities.

**Modern Period (20th Century to Present)**
After the 1950s, Tibetan society underwent major changes. Since the 1980s, China gradually opened Ngari Prefecture to international pilgrims. Today, Kailash remains an important destination for Tibetan Buddhists.`
