    historyEn: `**Prehistoric Period**
Bön's origins remain undated. One school maintains Bön was a prehistoric Tibetan belief closely connected to indigenous shamanic traditions. Archaeological evidence shows human activity on the Tibetan Plateau thousands of years ago; these early inhabitants likely had rudimentary sacred mountain worship.

**Early Bön (Before 7th Century)**
Before Buddhism arrived in Tibet, Bön was the plateau's primary religion. Characterized by nature worship, sacred mountain and lake rituals, divination, and shamanism. Kailash's concept as the "cosmic axis" likely formed during this period.

**Buddhist Arrival and Bön Reform (7th-11th Century)**
In the 7th century, Buddhism arrived from India. To meet this challenge, Bön underwent systematic reform, borrowing Buddhist doctrine, rituals, and canonical structures, forming "White Bön" or "Systematic Bön." During this period, Kailash's status in Bön scriptures was further strengthened.

**Bön-Buddhist Coexistence (11th Century to Present)**
Although Buddhism achieved dominance in Tibet, Bön has always maintained its independent traditions. Bön practitioners' counter-clockwise circumambulation marks this independence. Today, Bön still has considerable followers, especially in eastern and northern Tibet.`
